Plotting is easy in R

qplot(data = data, x = Q10_mother)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Plotting is flexible in R

ggplot(data = data, aes(x = Q10_mother, y = Q9_father)) + geom_jitter() + 
  stat_smooth(method = 'lm')
## Warning: Removed 7 rows containing missing values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 7 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Some bugs in the lab worksheet

  • Instead of ClassFall14$inlove_factor… you are going to use: data$Q8_fallinlove_factor <- factor(data$Q8_fallinlove)

  • Instead of x <- seq… you are going to use: x <- seq(50,80,0.5)

  • Some computers will not let you get frequency tables or numerical summaries. Try: table(data$Q8_fallinlove_factor) and summary(data$Q8_fallinlove)
